{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[G3 child-coverage — container review of parent 1f19-adf2-ffb2-4b09 paired with THIS child (S2 70c7: Content-addressed snapshot cache — cache read/populate path)]\n\nVERDICT: EMPTY G3 findings list. The union of the WHOLE eight-story roster (S1 6d56 materialize core, S2 70c7 THIS cache read/populate, S2b b73c janitor/reclamation, S3 fa49 gate threading, S4 30b3 attested signing, S4b e308 claim-gate coherence/ADR 0002, S5 b7fa CLI/MCP surfaces, S6 1ba5 docs) covers every parent acceptance/success criterion; no uncovered parent criterion is attributable to this pairing.\n\nGROUNDING NOTE (supersedes the two earliest comments on this ticket, which credited THIS child with the janitor + ADR via \"its AC3..AC12/AC13\"): those ACs are NOT in this child's CURRENT body. Its six ACs are purely the cache READ/POPULATE path (in-process single-flight, cross-process flock single-flight, delete-on-last-close reader safety, ENOENT/read-error self-heal, touch-on-read mtime LRU signal, populate-side byte-total increment). The janitor / reclamation / startup-sweep / trash-drain / gc-lock / tunables / ADR are explicitly scoped OUT to sibling S2b dodgy-luff-quasar (b73c), which IS present in the roster and owns them (b73c AC1-AC10). The ticket TITLE still reads \"+ background janitor\" — a residual stale label = a G4 staleness note, NOT a G3 coverage gap, since S2b covers that work.\n\n4-bucket coverage map (parent AC -> covering child/children; THIS child's role called out):\n\n- Parent AC1 (no code-reading gate reads the server working tree in attested mode; all read a faithful snapshot materialized at the pinned SHA) — FULLY covered by S1 (materialize core: read-tree+checkout-index, atomic population) + S3 (gate re-rooting onto the snapshot). STRUCTURAL w.r.t. THIS child: it CACHES the materialized entry but does not own materialization (Scope \"Out: materialization itself (S1)\"; What \"populated via S1's atomic dir-rename\"). Not an absence.\n\n- Parent AC2 (signed verdict binds verified_at_sha via the signed manifest channel; reproducible; no payload-schema/version change; prior signatures still verify) — FULLY covered by S4 (manifest-channel binding) atop S1's immutable-SHA basis. THIS child REINFORCES reproducibility (immutable SHA = no-staleness content-addressed key; a hit serves byte-identical content) but does not sign. STRUCTURAL w.r.t. this child. Not an absence.\n\n- Parent AC3 (local mode reads in-place AND cannot sign; documented back-out) — covered by S3 (in-place read; \"no materialization, no cache\" => local bypasses this cache) + S4 (signing bar) + S6 (docs). THIS child claims nothing here. STRUCTURAL w.r.t. this child. Not an absence.\n\n- Parent AC4 (concurrent gates on same/different SHAs run without git-lock contention or cross-op corruption; the snapshot cache + JANITOR reclaim disk under a defined free-space watermark (S2) WITHOUT disrupting in-flight reads) — FULLY covered, SPLIT cleanly: THIS child is PRIMARY OWNER of the single-flight + reader-safety half — its AC1 (two concurrent gates on the same SHA => exactly ONE materialization, the second reads the shared entry), AC2 (two PROCESSES racing => one materialization via flock(LOCK_EX)), AC3 (entry removed under an open fd does NOT disrupt the in-flight read — delete-on-last-close; new lookup cleanly misses + re-materializes), AC4 (ENOENT/read-error => miss => self-heal), AC5 (no PID/heartbeat lease). The JANITOR-reclaim sub-clause (\"reclaim disk under a defined free-space watermark without disrupting in-flight reads\") is owned by SIBLING S2b (b73c AC1/AC6 — rename-to-trash-not-in-place-rmtree riding THIS child's delete-on-last-close AC3). The no-worktree + no-index.lock/config.lock-contention + atomic-population half is owned by S1. No double-implementation; no gap. Not an absence.\n\n- Parent AC5 (private-repo fetch failure surfaces a descriptive, actionable credential error) — FULLY covered by S1 (raises the actionable error) + S6 (documents message + remedy + fail-closed/local-still-runs). Fetch is S1's coalesced step; this child claims none. STRUCTURAL w.r.t. this child. Not an absence.\n\n- Parent AC6 (portable: no external tar; no hardcoded /tmp; flock+mkdir fallback) — FULLY covered by S1 (pure-Python extraction, gettempdir/mkdtemp, fcntl.flock + atomic-mkdir fallback) + S6 (docs: tmpdir env, EFS/NFS flock caveat). THIS child's cross-process flock(LOCK_EX) on locks/<sha> RIDES that portability seam without re-owning the tar/tmp/flock-fallback sub-clauses. STRUCTURAL w.r.t. this child. Not an absence.\n\n- Parent AC7 (operational tunables — free-space watermark, default ref, grace/age windows — configurable with documented defaults (S2/S3)) — watermark + grace/age window tunables owned by S2b (b73c AC9: \"Watermark, grace window, max-age, and reverify period are configurable with documented defaults\"); default ref owned by S3 (fa49) / surfaced by S5; docs by S6. THIS child's CURRENT body carries no tunables AC (they live with the janitor on S2b). Covered by the roster; NOT an absence at this child.\n\n- Parent AC8 (an ADR captures the architecture + rejected alternatives: PID-lease, payload-schema SHA binding) — cache/janitor-architecture + rejected PID+heartbeat-lease ADR owned by S2b (b73c AC10; matches the parent ADR-section \"authored in S2/S4\"); the payload-schema SHA-binding rejected alternative owned by S4 (30b3); ADR 0002 owned by S4b (e308). THIS child's CURRENT body carries no ADR AC — and need not, because named siblings cover every rejected-alternative clause. Covered-by-named-consumer; NOT an absence.\n\n- Parent final AC (all EIGHT enumerated child stories closed; make lint + full test suite green) — STRUCTURAL/meta epic-completion criterion; covered by the existence of all eight children in the roster (this is story S2 of 8) + each child's own green-bar obligation. Not an absence at this child.\n\nSuccess-criteria narrative (\"every code-reading gate verifies a client-specified, immutable, reproducible snapshot at a pinned SHA — never the server's mutable checkout — SAFELY UNDER CONCURRENT DISTRIBUTED USE; signed verdicts bind verified_at_sha via the manifest channel; local preserves the single-developer verify-before-push workflow\") decomposes onto parent AC1-AC8. The \"SAFELY UNDER CONCURRENT USE\" clause splits across THIS child's single-flight + delete-on-last-close reader safety (the read path) and S2b's reclaim-without-corrupting-readers (the janitor); the immutable-SHA content-addressed cache key (no staleness) is what makes \"reproducible snapshot\" hold across cache hits; the \"signed/reproducible/verified_at_sha\" clause -> S4; the \"unsigned local verify-before-push\" clause -> S3. No uncovered obligation introduced by this child's existence.\n\nNamed-consumer / delegation cross-checks (covered-by-named-consumer, not absences): materialization -> S1 (named in this child's What+Scope); janitor/reclamation/tunables/ADR -> S2b b73c (named in this child's Why+Scope: \"RECLAMATION ... is the sibling janitor story\"; \"Out: eviction / janitor / disk reclamation (sibling janitor story)\"); verdict signing -> S4; verdict memoization -> deferred fast-follow (parent Out-of-scope). Each delegated obligation is claimed by a named sibling present in the roster or is out of epic scope.\n\nNote (NOT a G3 finding): the standing G6/G4 seam on the parent and on sibling S4 (30b3) — routing the pinned-SHA snapshot handle into plan_review/attest.py's dependency_hashes()/_rehash()/ADR-0002 freshness re-check (which still root on _config.repo_root) — is a consistency/mechanism concern about WHO threads the snapshot handle between S3/S4/S4b, not a G3 union-coverage gap, and is unrelated to this cache read/populate child. The corresponding parent obligations (AC1 snapshot-only reads, AC2 reproducibility) remain CLAIMED by children, so the union covers them.\n\nConclusion: this child cleanly covers the cache READ/POPULATE slice (content-addressed SHA-keyed layout, in-process + cross-process single-flight, delete-on-last-close reader safety, touch-on-read mtime LRU signal, populate-side byte-total increment, read-error self-heal) of the parent criteria — co-owner of the concurrency half of parent AC4 and supplier of the read-side primitives (mtime LRU signal, byte-total, delete-on-last-close) that S2b's janitor consumes for AC4's reclaim clause. Every parent acceptance/success criterion has a named owner in the eight-story roster; none is left uncovered. NO G3 finding for this pairing (the janitor/ADR/tunables being absent from THIS child is correctly delegated to sibling S2b b73c — not a coverage gap)."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782532915443389001,"uuid":"c029d4b8-2a45-4743-8a15-51891b172f9c"}